## Secrets Management

### Ansible Vault Operations

```bash # View encrypted vault contents ansible-vault view /opt/ansible/vars/vault.yml

# Edit encrypted vault ansible-vault edit /opt/ansible/vars/vault.yml

# Encrypt existing file ansible-vault encrypt /opt/ansible/vars/plaintext.yml

# Decrypt file (not recommended - creates plaintext) ansible-vault decrypt /opt/ansible/vars/vault.yml

# Change vault password ansible-vault rekey /opt/ansible/vars/vault.yml ```

### Environment File Management

```bash # Generate .env files from Ansible Vault ansible-playbook /opt/ansible/playbooks/generate-env-files.yml

# View .env file contents cat /opt/docker/.env

# Check .env file permissions ls -la /opt/docker/.env # Should show: -rw——- (0600)

# Verify Docker Compose reads .env cd /opt/docker docker compose config | grep PASSWORD # Should show actual passwords, not ${VARIABLES} ```

### Password Rotation

```bash # PostgreSQL password change docker exec -it postgres psql -U postgres ALTER USER username WITH PASSWORD 'NEW_PASSWORD'; \q

# MariaDB password change docker exec -it mariadb mysql -u root -p ALTER USER 'username'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'NEW_PASSWORD'; ALTER USER 'username'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY 'NEW_PASSWORD'; FLUSH PRIVILEGES; EXIT;

# After password change in database: # 1. Update password in Ansible Vault ansible-vault edit /opt/ansible/vars/vault.yml

# 2. Regenerate .env files ansible-playbook /opt/ansible/playbooks/generate-env-files.yml

# 3. Restart affected containers docker compose restart service_name ```

### Database Connection Testing

```bash # Test PostgreSQL connection docker exec -it postgres psql -U username -d database -W # Enter password

# Test MariaDB connection docker exec -it mariadb mysql -u username -p database # Enter password

# Test from application perspective docker logs service_name –tail 50 # Look for “Access denied” or “authentication failed” ```
